5: The data visualizations and general data can be used to make many inferences and solidify assumptions to concrete statements above. The data to begin with is about Washington D.C. residential properties. 49 variables are used to help sort and categorize the properties in D.C. Variables range from the number of bathrooms, rooms, stories in the house to the house quality assignment by contractors . I wanted to explore the size aspect of the homes, by seeing the patterns in the number of rooms. In addition, analyse which category of grading assignment is usually given to D.C. properties. I wanted to explore these two varibales, because often times there is a perception that residential properties in Washington D.C. are rundown and small in space available. While, this may be true for a certain portion of residences, expecially in urban cities. I want to explore if this is actually an assumption or a true reality according to this data.

It is important to take into account of missing values so when making visualization and other inferences of data ,one knows how much data they are working with. The sum of all missing data values is 1356686, which is only 17.4% of the whole data set. That is not a bad number considering the amount of numerical data in the data set. Also, all the data was regiestered as NA, but for a couple of na, which were converted to NA. Then the barchart of the quality distribution of D.C. residences cearly shows that Average category has the highest frequency, preceded by Good and then Very Good. Having Average as a benchmark is good when it comes ot housing quality in a mass scale , especially in urban cities. However, it is important to be aware of the fact that the requirement of what makes a property average is uknown to me for this data set. So for someone, who is actually using this in a real life setting should inquire about that. However, having good,and very good is a good sign, rather than poor and fair. This shows that most of the properties in Washington D.C. are average or above average. Another observation, I made is that excellent properties are basically close to zero. This could be because there is very a shortage of economic resouces and management required to elevate a very good propery to an excellent property.

The next category, is number rooms. Oftem times, the more the number of rooms the bigger the house. Also, I wanted to get a feel on average how much space is available for people. This coule be seen by a histogram. The histogram shows that most of the data is clustered 1-5 rooms, with 2 rooms having the most frequency. The data is skewed to the right, with the tail. There are, but, very few prperties wil more than 5 rooms. Also, take note that rooms is all the rooms in the house, not just bedrooms. This speeks to actually how much limited space is available in properties in Washington D.C. ou can also embed plots, for example:

#Question: Are the mean of of rooms for Qualified and Unqualified equal to one another? 
boxplot(dcprop$rooms~dcprop$QUALIFIED)

# The first assumtpion is that the sample must be random, which for my data set that is true because the properties used for this data set were chosen on a random lottery basis for this project. The random variable is normally distributed, and the random variable is reffered as assumption b. 
#H0: mean rooms of Qualified properties = mean rooms of Unqualified properties
#HA:  mean rooms of Qualified properties != mean rooms of Unqualified properties
# mean two sided t-tests
t.test(dcprop$rooms~dcprop$QUALIFIED, mu=0, alt="two.sided", conf=0.95, var.eq=T, paired=F)
## 
##  Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  dcprop$rooms by dcprop$QUALIFIED
## t = -36.262, df = 158955, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.5003183 -0.4490064
## sample estimates:
## mean in group Q mean in group U 
##        5.941060        6.415722
#p-value < 2.2e-16
# Since, the p-value is less than 0.05, the null hypothesis is rejected
# There is enough evidence to show that the mean rooms of qualified prperties is not equal to the mean rooms of unqualified propertie

chisq.test(table(dcprop$rooms,dcprop$bathroom))

## X-squared = 406766, df = 546, p-value < 2.2e-16
# p-value < 2.2e-16
# Reject the null hypothesis, because H0<0.05
# There is enough evidence to conclude that the number of rooms and bathrooms are dependent of one another.

#9 The relationship between rooms and their qualifications is interesting. One may thing only homes qualified of being sold would have rooms in equal proprtion because if there is no room, then how is it going to be on the market? The boxplot firstly exhbits the variances and distribution of the two variables. This also can be seen with the var function. Then the null hypothesis was that both the mean of rooms for qualified and unqualfied rooms would be equal. The t-test showed other wise because the p-value was < 0.05. Hence, there was enough evidence that showed that both were independent of one another. This implies that the number rooms is not only factor that influences a room being qualified or unqualified.

Then the chi-sqaured test was showing if the number of rooms and bathrooms are indpenedent of one another. Typically, the more the number of rooms, the more is the number of bathrooms. However, the chi-squared test would confirm or deny that. First, a contingency table was made to show this and then inserted into the chisquared test. Since, the p-value was less than 0.05 the null hypothesis is rejected, it can be concluded that the number of rooms and bathrooms are dependent on one another.
